{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Sir Alfred William Flux |caption = |birth_date = 8 April 1867 |birth_place = [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]], UK |death_date = 16 July 1942 |death_place = [[Faxe Ladeplads]], [[Zealand]], Denmark |residence = UK, Canada, Denmark |citizenship = British |nationality = |ethnicity = |field = [[Economics]], [[Statistics]] |work_institutions = [[Manchester University]], [[McGill University]] |alma_mater = [[St John's College, Cambridge]] |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = [[Guy Medal]] {{small|(Silver, 1921) (Gold, 1930)}} |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }} '''Sir Alfred William Flux''' [[CB (Honour)|CB]] (8 April 1867&nbsp;– 16 July 1942) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[economist]] and [[statistician]].
Flux was born in the [[Landport]] district of [[Portsmouth]] in 1867, the son of a cement maker.<ref name=gw/> He attended [[Portsmouth Grammar School]] then studied mathematics at [[St John's College, Cambridge]] where he was a [[Senior Wrangler]] in 1887<ref name=venn>{{acad|id=FLS884AW|name=Flux, Alfred William}}</ref> (sharing the honour in a tie with three others). While at Cambridge he became friends with [[Alfred Marshall]], who interested him in economics. He was a foundation member of the Economic Society (1890), and from 1893 until 1908 taught economics, at Manchester and then at [[McGill University]], Montreal.<ref name=nature>{{cite journal| journal=Nature| title=Obituary: Sir Alfred William Flux, C.B| volume=150 |page= 228 |year= 1942 | doi=10.1038/150228a0 |last=Bowley | first=A. L. | authorlink=A. L. Bowley | issue=3799}}</ref> In 1897, while in Manchester he married Harriet Emily Hansen, a Danish woman.<ref name=gw/>
Flux returned to London in 1908 to take up a post as advisor to the Commercial, Labour and Statistics Department. In 1918, he was appointed Head of the Statistics Department of the [[Board of Trade]].<ref name=gw>{{cite journal|last=Groenewegen|first= Peter|title= Alfred William Flux (1867–1942): a mathematician successfully ‘caught’ for economics by Marshall|journal=History of Economics Review |volume= 48 | year=2008| pages=63–77|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_6787/is_48/ai_n31847312/}}</ref> The [[Royal Statistical Society]] awarded him the [[Guy Medal]] in Silver in 1921 and in Gold in 1930. He also served as President of the Society between 1928 and 1930.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rss.org.uk/site/cms/contentviewarticle.asp?article=486 |title=Royal Statistical Society Presidents |publisher=Royal Statistical Society |accessdate=6 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317044817/http://www.rss.org.uk/site/cms/contentviewarticle.asp?article=486 |archivedate=17 March 2012 }}</ref>
Flux retired to Denmark in 1932 and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1934. He died of pneumonia in 1942, aged 75.<ref name=gw/><ref name=venn/>
