== H ==
{{glossary}}

{{term|1=harmonic}}
{{defn|no=1|Two pairs of points on a line are harmonic if their cross ratio is –1. The 4 points are called a '''harmonic set''', and the points of one pair are called '''harmonic conjugates''' with respect to the other pair. }}
{{defn|no=2|A harmonic cubic is an elliptic curve with ''j''-invariant 1728, given by a double cover of the projective line branched at 4 points with cross ratio –1.}}
{{defn|no=3|Satisfying some analogue of the [[Laplace equation]], as in harmonic form.}}
{{defn|no=4|The '''harmonic polar line''' of an inflection point of a cubic curve is the component of the polar conic other than the tangent line. {{harv|Dolgachev|2012|loc=3.1.2}} }}
{{defn|no=5|A '''harmonic net''' is a set of points on a line containing the harmonic conjugate of any point with respect to any other two points. {{harv|Baker|1922|loc=p.133}} }}
{{defn|no=6|For harmonically conjugate conics see {{harv|Baker|1922|loc=vol 2, p.122}}. }}

{{term|Hesse}}
{{term|1=Hessian }}
{{defn|Named after [[Otto Hesse]].}}
{{defn|no=1|1=A [[Hessian matrix]], or a variety associated with it. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p.55}}.}}
{{defn|no=2|The Hessian line is a line associated to 3 points ''A'', ''B'', ''C'', of a conic, containing the three points given by the intersections of the tangents at ''A'', ''B'', ''C'' with the lines ''BC'', ''CA'', ''AB''. }}
{{defn|no=3|The Hessian point is a point associated to three lines tangent to a conic, whose construction is dual to that of a Hessian line.}}
{{defn|no=4|The [[Hessian pair]] or Hessian duad of three points on a projective line is the pair of points fixed by the projective transformations of order 3 permuting the 3 points. More generally the Hessian pair is also defined in a similar way for triples of points of a rational curve, or triples of elements of a pencil. }}
{{defn|no=5|The [[Hesse configuration]] is the configuration of inflection points of a plane cubic.}}
{{defn|no=6|The [[Hesse group]] is the group of automorphisms of the Hesse configuration, of order 216.}}

{{term|1=hexad}}
{{defn|1=A set of 6 points}}

{{term|1=homaloid}}
{{defn|An element of a homaloidal system, in particular the image of a hyperlpane under a [[Cremona transformation]].}}
{{term| homaloidal}}
{{defn|no=1|1=
A homaloidal linear system of divisors is a linear system of grade 1, such as the image of the linear system of hyperplanes of projective space under a [[Cremona transformation]]. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.45}} {{harv|Coolidge|1931|loc=p. 442}} When the linear system has dimension 2 or 3 it is called a '''homaloidal net''' or '''homaloidal web'''.}}
{{defn|no=2|Homaloidal means similar to a flat plane. }}

{{term|1= homographic }}
{{defn|no=1| Having the same invariants. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p.232  }}.}}
{{defn|no=2|A homographic transformation is an automorphism of projective space over a field, in other words an element of the projective general linear group. {{harv|Salmon|1879|loc=p.283  }}}}

{{term|homography}}
{{defn|no=1|An isomorphism between projective spaces induced by an isomorphism of vector spaces.}}
{{defn|no=2|An '''axis of homography''' is a line associated to two related ranges of a conic. {{harv|Baker|1922|loc=vol2, p.16}} }}

{{term|homology}}
{{defn|no=1|As in [[homology group]]}}
{{defn|no=2|A collineation fixing all lines through a point (the center) and all points through a line (the axis) not containing the center. See elation. This terminology was introduced by Lie.}}
{{defn|no=3|An automorphism of projective space with a hyperplane of fixed points (called the '''axis'''). It is called a '''harmonic homology''' if it has order 2, in which case it has an isolated fixed point called its '''center'''.}}

{{term|Hurwitz curve}}
{{term|Hurwitz surface|multi=y}}
{{defn|A [[Hurwitz curve]] is a complex algebraic curve of genus ''g''>0 with the maximum possible number 84(''g''–1) of automorphisms.}}

{{term|1= hyperbolism }}
{{defn|1=  Essentially a blow-up of a curve at a point. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p.175  }}.}}

{{term|hypercusp}}
{{defn|A singularity of a curve of some multiplicity ''r'' whose tangent cone is a single line meeting the curve with order ''r''+1. {{harv|Coolidge|1931|loc=p. 18}}}}

{{term|1=hyperelliptic}}
{{defn|1=A [[hyperelliptic curve]] is a curve with a degree 2 map to the projective line.}}

{{term|hyperflex}}
{{defn|Same as point of undulation: a point of a curve where the tangent line has contact of order at least 4.}}

{{term|hyperosculating point}}
{{defn|A point where the tangent space meets with order higher than normal. }}

{{term|hyperplane}}
{{defn|A linear subspace of projective space of codimension 1. Same as prime.}}

