{{defn|no=2|Tangent to some lines, as in [[inscribed circle]].}}

{{term|integral}}
{{defn || An integral is (more or less) what is now called a closed differential form, or sometimes the result of integrating such a form.}}
{{defn|no=1|An integral of the first kind is a holomorphic closed differential form.}}
{{defn|no=2|An integral of the second kind is a meromorphic closed differential form with no residues.}}
{{defn|no=3|An integral of the third kind is a meromorphic closed differential form whose poles are all simple.}}
{{defn|no=4|A simple integral is a closed 1-form, or the result of integrating a 1-form.}}
{{defn|no=5|A double integral is a closed 2-form, or the result of integrating a 2-form.}}

{{term|invariant}}
{{defn|(Noun) A polynomial in the coefficients of a homogeneous form, invariant under some group of linear transformations. See also covariant, contravariant, concomitant.}}

{{term|1= inversion}}
{{defn|1= An [[inversive geometry|inversion]] is a transformation of order 2 exchanging the inside and outside of a circle. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p.103  }}.}}

{{term|1= involute }}
{{defn|1= An [[involute]] is a curve obtained by unrolling a string around a curve. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p. 278 }}.}}

{{term|involution}}
{{defn|no=1|A transformation whose square is the identity.  [[Cremona transformation]]s that are involutions include [[Bertini involution]]s, [[Geiser involution]]s, and [[De Jonquières involution]]s.}}

{{term|1=irregularity  }}
{{defn|1=The [[irregularity of a surface]] is the dimension of the space of holomorphic 1-forms on a non-singular projective surface; see [[Hodge number]].}}

{{term|isologue}}
{{defn|1=Given a Cremoma transformation ''T'', the isologue of a point ''p'' is the set of points ''x'' such that ''p'', ''x'', ''T''(''x'') are collinear. The point ''p'' is called the center of the isologue.}}

{{glossary end}}

