{{term|1=pippian}}
{{defn|1= Introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Cayley|year=1857}}. Now called the [[Cayleyan]]. See also quippian. }}

{{term|Plücker }}
{{defn|{{main|Julius Plücker}} }}
{{defn|no=1|For Plücker characteristic see characteristic}}
{{defn|no=2|A [[Plücker line]] is one of the 15 lines containing 4 of the 20 Steiner points associated to 6 points on a conic. The Plücker lines meet in threes at the 60 Kirkman points. {{harv|Dolgachev|2012|loc=p.124}} }}

{{term|plurigenus}}
{{defn|Plural '''plurigenera'''}}
{{defn|The ''d''th [[plurigenus]] of a variety is the dimension of the space of sections of the ''d''th power of the canonical line bundle.}}

{{term|point-star}}
{{defn|A family of lines with a common point}}

{{term|1=polar}}
{{defn|no=1|1=(Adjective) Related by a polarity}}
{{defn|no=2|The polar conic is the zero set of the quadratic form associated to a polarity, or equivalently the set of self-conjugate points of the polarity.}}
{{defn|no=3|1=(Noun) The first polar, second polar, and so on are varieties of degrees ''n''–1, ''n''–2, ... formed from a point and a hypersurface of degree ''n'' by polarizing the equation of the hypersurface. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.11}}}}
{{defn|no=4| A '''polar''' or '''polar line''' is the line corresponding to a point under a polarity of the projective plane.}}

{{term|1=polarity}}
{{defn|1=A correlation given by a symmetrical matrix, or a correlation of period 2. A polarity of the projective space of a vector space is essentially a non-degenerate symmetric bilinear form, up to multiplication by scalars. See also null-polarity. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.9}}}}

{{term|1=pole}}
{{defn|no=1|1= The point corresponding to a hyperplane under a polarity.}}
{{defn|no=2|1= A singularity of a rational function.}}

{{term|poloconic}}
{{term|polocubic|multi=y}}
{{term|poloquartic|multi=y}}
{{defn|The poloconic (also called conic polar) of a line in the plane with respect to a cubic curve is the locus of points whose first polar is tangent to the line. {{harv|Dolgachev|2012|loc=p. 156–157}} }}

{{term|polygonal}}
{{defn|A polygonal (or ''k''-gonal) curve is a curve together with a map (of degree ''k'') to the projective line. The degree of the map is called the gonality of the curve. When the degree is 1, 2, or 3 the curve is called rational, hyperelliptic, or trigonal.}}

{{term|1=porism}}
{{defn|no=1|1=A [[porism]] is a corollary, especially in geometry, as in [[Poncelet's porism]]. The precise meaning seems to be controversial.}}
{{defn|no=2|1=An arrangement of geometrical figures (such as lines or circles) that are inscribed in one curve and circumscribed around another, as in [[Poncelet's porism]] or [[Steiner's porism]]. There seems to be some confusion about whether "porism" refers to the geometrical configuration or to the statement of the result.}}
{{term|poristic}}
{{defn|Having either no solutions or infinitely many {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.186}}. For example, [[Poncelet's porism]] and [[Steiner's porism]] imply that if there is one way to arrange lines or circles then there are infinitely many ways. }}

{{term|postulated}}
{{defn| A postulated object (point, line, and so on) is an object in some larger space. For example, a point at infinity of projective space is a postulated point of affine space. {{harv|Baker|1922}} }}

{{term|1=postulation}}
{{defn|1=The postulation of a variety for some family is the number of independent conditions needed to force an elements of the family to contain the variety. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.440}} }}

{{term|power of a point}}
{{defn|Laguerre defined the [[power of a point]] with respect to an algebraic curve of degree ''n'' to be the product of the distances from the point to the intersections with a circle through it, divided by the ''n''th power of the diameter. He showed that this is independent of the choice of circle through the point. {{harv|Coolidge|1931|loc=p.176}} }}

{{term|1=prime}}
{{defn|1= An old term for a hyperplane in a [[projective space]]. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.1}}}}

{{term|1=primal}}
{{defn|1= An old term for a [[projective hypersurface]]. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.10}}}}

{{term|1=projectivity}}
{{defn|1=An isomorphism between two projective lines (or ranges). A projectivity is a product of at most three perspectivities.}}

{{term|propinquity}}
{{defn|A number depending on two branches at a point, defined by {{harvtxt|Coolidge|1931|loc=p. 224}}.
