== Q ==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1=quadratic transformation}}
{{defn|no=1|1=A Cremona transformation of degree 2. A standard quadratic transformation is one similar to the map taking each coordinate to its inverse.}}
{{defn|no=2|1=A monomial transformation with center a point, or in other words a blowup at a point.}}

{{term|1=quadric}}
{{defn|1=Degree 2, especially a degree 2 projective variety. Not to be confused with quantic or quartic.}}

{{term|1=quadrisecant}}
{{defn|1=A [[quadrisecant]] is a line meeting something in four points}}

{{term|1=quadro-cubic, quadro-quartic}}
{{defn|1=A quadro-cubic or quadro-quartic transformation is a Cremona transformation such that the homaloids of the transformation have degree 2 and those of its inverse have degree 3 or 4. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.180, 188}}}}

{{term|1=quantic}}
{{defn|1=A homogeneous polynomial in several variables, now usually called a form. Not to be confused with quartic or quadric.}}

{{term|1=quarto-quartic}}
{{defn|1=A Quarto-quartic transformation is a Cremona transformation such that the homaloids of the transformation and its inverse all have degree 4. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.187}}}}

{{term|1=quaternary}}
{{defn|Depending on four variables, as in quaternary form.}}

{{term|1=quartic}}
{{defn|1=Degree 4, especially a degree 4 projective variety. Not to be confused with quantic or quadric.}}

{{term|1=quintic}}
{{defn|1=Degree 5, especially a degree 5 projective variety.}}

{{term|1=quippian}}
{{defn|1= A [[quippian]] is a degree 5 class 3 contravariant of a plane cubic introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Cayley|year=1857}} and discussed by {{harvtxt|Dolgachev|2012|loc=p.157}}. See also pippian.}}

{{term|quotient ring}}
{{defn|The quotient ring of a point (or more generally a subvariety) is what is now called its [[local ring]], formed by adding inverses to all functions that do not vanish identically on it.}}

{{glossary end}}

