{{defn|1= One of Cayley's names for the [[Cayleyan]]. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p. 352 }}.}}

{{term|1=surface}}
{{defn|1=An abstract surface together with an embedding into projective space.}}

{{term|1=superabundance of a divisor on a surface. }}
{{defn|1=The dimension of the first cohomology group of the corresponding sheaf. }}

{{term|1=symmetroid}}
{{defn|The zeros of the determinant of a symmetric matrix of linear forms}}

{{term|1=syntheme}}
{{defn|A partition of a set of 6 elements into 3 pairs, or an element of the symmetric group on 6 points of cycle shape 222. {{harv|Dolgachev|2012}}}}

{{term|1=system}}
{{defn|A family of algebraic sets in projective space; for example, a line system is a family of lines.}}

{{term|1=syzygetic}}
{{defn|Paired. Opposite of azygetic, meaning unpaired. Example: syzygetic triad, syzygetic tetrad, syzygetic set, [[syzygetic pencil]].}}

{{term|1=syzygy}}
{{defn|no=1|A point is in syzygy with some other points if it is in the linear subspace generated by them. {{harv|Baker|1922|loc=vol I, p. 33}} A syzygy is a linear relation between points in an affine space.}}
{{defn|no=2|An algebraic relation between generators of a ring, especially a ring of invariants or covariants.}}
{{defn|no=3|A linear relation between generators of a module, or more generally an element of the kernel of a homomorphism of modules.}}
{{defn|no=4|A global syzygy is a resolution of a module or sheaf.}}
{{glossary end}}

== T ==
{{glossary}}

{{term|1=tacnode}}
{{defn|1= A [[tacnode]] is a point of a curve where two branches meet in the same direction. {{harv|Cayley|1852}}}}

{{term|tacnode-cusp}}
{{defn|A singularity of a plane curve where a tacnode and a cusp are combined at the same point. {{harv|Salmon|1879|loc=p.207}}}}

{{term|1= tact-invariant }}
{{defn|1=  An invariant of two curves that vanishes if they touch each other. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p.76}}.}}

{{term|tangent cone}}
{{defn|A [[tangent cone]] is a cone defined by the non-zero terms of smallest degree in the Taylor series at a point of a hypersurface.}}

{{term|tangential equation}}
{{defn|The tangential equation of a plane curve is an equation giving the condition for a line to be tangent to the curve. In other words it is the equation of the dual curve. It is not the equation of a tangent to a curve.}}

{{term|1=ternary}}
{{defn|Depending on three variables, as in [[ternary form]]}}

{{term|1=tetrad}}
{{defn|1=A set of 4 points}}

{{term|1=tetragram}}
{{defn|1=Synonym for [[complete quadrilateral]]}}

{{term|1=tetrahedroid}}
{{defn|1=A [[tetrahedroid]] is a special kind of [[Kummer surface]].}}

{{term|1=tetrahedron}}
{{defn|A geometric configuration consisting of 4 points and the 6 lines joining pairs. This is similar to the lines and infinite edges of a polyhedral [[tetrahedron]], but in algebraic geometry one sometimes does not include the faces of the tetrahedron.}}

{{term|1=tetrastigm}}
{{defn|1=Synonym for [[complete quadrangle]]}}

{{term|third kind}}
{{defn|All poles are simple (order 1)}}

{{term|threefold}}
{{defn|no=1|(Adjective) Three-dimensional}}
{{defn|no=2|(Noun) A 3-dimensional variety}}

{{term|1=torsal generator.}}
{{defn|A generator of a scroll (ruled surface) that meets its consecutive generator. See {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.204}}.}}

{{term|1=torse }}
{{defn|1=[[Developable surface]].}}
{{term|transvectant}}
{{defn|An invariant depending on two forms. }}

{{term|1=transversal}}
{{defn|1=A line meeting several other lines. For example, 4 generic lines in projective 3-space have 2 transversals meeting all of them.}}

{{term|1=triad}}
{{defn|1=A set of 3 points}}

{{term|tricircular}}
{{defn|A [[tricircular curve]] is one that passes through the circular points at infinity with order 3.}}

{{term|1=tricuspidal}}
{{defn|1=Having three cusps}}

{{term|trigonal}}
{{defn|A trigonal curve is one with a degree three map to the projective line. See hyperelliptic.}}

{{term|trihedral}}
{{defn|A set of 3 planes A Steiner trihedral is a set of three tritangent planes of a cubic surface whose intersection point is not on the surface. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.152}} }}

{{term|1=trilinear coordinates}}
{{defn|1=Coordinates based on distance from sides of a triangle: [[Trilinear coordinates]].}}

{{term|1=trinodal}}
{{defn|1=Having three nodes}}

{{term|1=tripartite}}
{{defn|1=Having three connected components. {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p.165  }}}}

{{term|1=trisecant}}
{{defn|1=A line meeting a variety in 3 points. See [[trisecant identity]].}}

{{term|1=tritangent}}
{{defn|1=Meeting something in 3 tangent points, such as a tritangent conic to a cubic curve or a tritangent plane of a cubic surface.}}

{{term|1=trope}}
{{defn|1= A [[trope (mathematics)|trope]] is a singular (meaning special) tangent space. {{harv|Cayley|1869|loc=p.202}} The word is mostly used for a tangent space of a [[Kummer surface]] touching it along a conic.}}

{{term|1=twisted }}
{{defn|1=A [[twisted cubic]] is a degree 3 embedding of the projective line in projective 3-space}}

{{term|total}}
{{defn|A set of 5 partitions of a 6-element set into three pairs, such that no two elements of the total have a pair in common. For example,  {(12)(36)(45), (13)(24)(56), (14)(26)(35), (15)(23)(46), (16)(25)(34)} {{harv|Dolgachev|2012}}}}

{{term|type}}
{{defn|The type of a projective surface is the number of tangent planes meeting a generic linear subspace of codimension 4. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.193}}}}

{{glossary end}}

== U ==
{{glossary}}

{{term|1= undulation }}
{{defn|1=  A point of undulation of a curve is where the tangent meets the curve to fourth order; also called a hyperflex. See inflection point. {{harv|Salmon|1879|loc=p.35, 211  }}}}

{{term|unibranch}}
{{defn|Having only one branch at a point. For example, a cusp of a plane curve is unibranch, while a node is not.}}

{{term|1= unicursal  }}
{{defn|1=  A unicursal curve is one that is [[rational variety|rational]], in other words birational to the projective line. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p. 29 }}.}}

{{term|1= unipartite }}
{{defn|1=  [[Connected (topology)|Connected]]. See {{harvtxt|Salmon|1879|loc=p.165  }}}}

{{term|1=unirational}}
{{defn|no=1|1=A correspondence is called unirational if it is generically injective, in other words a rational map. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.20}} }}
{{defn|no=2|A variety is called [[unirational]] if it is finitely covered by a rational variety.}}

{{term|1=united point}}
{{defn|1=A point in the intersection of the diagonal and a correspondence from a set to itself.}}

{{term|1=unode}}
{{defn|1= A double point of a surface whose tangent cone consists of one double plane. See binode.}}

{{glossary end}}

== V ==
{{glossary}}

{{term|valence}}
{{term|valency|multi=y}}
{{defn|The valence or valency of a correspondence ''T'' on a curve is a number ''k'' such that the divisors  ''T''(''P'')+''kP'' are all linearly equivalent. A correspondence need not have a valency. {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.368}}}}

{{term|1=Veronese surface}}
{{defn|1={{main|Veronese surface}} An embedding of the projective plane in 5-dimensional projective space.}}

{{term|1=virtual}}
{{defn|1=An estimate for something that is often but not always correct, such as virtual genus, virtual dimension, and so on. If some number is given by the dimension of a space of sections of some sheaf, the corresponding virtual number is sometimes given by the corresponding Euler characteristic, and equal to the dimension when all higher cohomology groups vanish. See superabundance.}}

{{glossary end}}

== W ==
{{glossary}}

{{term|1=web}}
{{defn|1= A 3-dimensional linear system. See "net" and "pencil". {{harv|Semple|Roth|1949|loc=p.160}}}}

{{term|Weddle surface}}
{{defn|1={{main|Weddle surface}} A quartic surface in projective space given by the locus of the vertex of a cone passing through 6 points in general position.}}

{{term|Weierstrass point}}
{{defn|{{Main|Weierstrass point}} A point on a curve where the dimension of the space of rational functions whose only singularity is a pole of some order at the point is higher than normal. }}

{{term|Wirtinger sextic}}
{{defn|{{main|Wirtinger sextic}} A degree 4 genus 6 plane curve with nodes at the 6 points of a [[complete quadrangle]].}}

{{glossary end}}

